I hope my tutorial series is helpful. I&#39;m not sure that SharpNEAT is
something a C# novice wants to dive into, to be honest. If you simply want
to get a project of your own up and running, then following the tutorials
will certainly help you do that. If you&#39;re looking for more insight into
how the NEAT algorithm itself is implemented, as it sounds like Adele is,
then I would really not recommend SharpNEAT.

The SharpNEAT framework is huge, the modularity of it can make it
intimidating, and there are tons of low-level optimizations Colin has made
that obscure things. If you do not feel confident in C#, but you wish to
implement/understand a C# version of NEAT, then my suggestion would be to
first get more experience with C#. It&#39;s a simple enough language that
anyone with an OO background can pick it up quickly.

As Drew mentioned, there are implementations available in almost every
language now, so if you&#39;re strong in another language, it may be a better
move to look at that version. Ken has a list of different implementations
available here: http://www.cs.ucf.edu/~kstanley/#software


Wesley

